<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1902-06-20T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1902-06-20T00:00:00-05:00" n="811" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d811">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Merry</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Hay</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of the United States</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">San José</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1902-06-20"><hi rend="italic">June 20,
                                1902</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 734.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to advise the receipt of
                            a telegram dated this day from the Hon. Fernando Sanchez, minister of
                            foreign relations of the Republic of Nicaragua, informing me that his
                            Government will be pleased to permit consular officers of the United
                            States to use their good offices on behalf of the citizens of the
                            Republic of Cuba resident in or visiting Nicaragua. Of this I have
                            advised United States consuls in Nicaragua in accordance with your
                            instructions.</p>
                        <p>With assurances, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">William Lawrence
                            Merry.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                </body></text></TEI>